You can use the `` floor() `` and `` modulo() `` methods to create the desired format. Here's an example code:


```javascript
function getNumberSpaces(num, spaceLen) {
  const result = [];
  for (let i = 0; i < num; i++) {
    const start = i % (spaceLen * 2) - spaceLen;
    const end = i % (spaceLen * 2) + spaceLen;
    result.push({ start, ende });
  }
  return result;
}

```

This function takes in the number and the length of the spaces between the numbers. For example, in the case of `` 1.000 `` and `` 100 ``, the function will return:


```json
[
  { start:0, ende:99 },
  { start:100, ende:199 },
  { start:200, ende:299 },
  { start:300, ende:399 },
  ...
]

```

Note that the function uses the `` % `` operator to calculate the start and end indices of each space, which will be valid for both small and large numbers.
